The paper discusses garbage collection in the context of a specific programming language, MIT/GNU Scheme, which suggests that it falls under the programming languages (cs.PL) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on measuring the effectiveness of garbage collection, which could also place it in the software engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The experiments conducted in the paper involve measuring the drag time of objects, which could be seen as a performance optimization technique, potentially placing it in the distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also discusses opportunities for improving garbage collection, which could be seen as a form of optimization or logic (cs.LO). Finally, the paper's focus on memory management and potential memory savings could also place it in the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category.
